# Unity/C# Development Principles

## Core Architecture
- Use **MonoBehaviour** for script components attached to GameObjects
- Prefer **ScriptableObjects** for data containers and shared resources
- Follow **Component pattern** strictly for clear separation of concerns and modularity
- Structure project in a modular way using Unity's component-based architecture

## Key Guidelines
- Write clear, technical responses with precise C# and Unity examples
- Use Unity's built-in features and tools wherever possible
- Prioritize readability and maintainability
- Follow C# coding conventions and Unity best practices
- Use descriptive variable and function names

## Naming Conventions
- **PascalCase** for public members and methods
- **camelCase** for private members and local variables
- Use descriptive names that clearly indicate purpose and functionality

## Unity-Specific Features
- Leverage Unity's **physics engine** and collision detection system
- Use Unity's **Input System** for handling player input across platforms
- Utilize Unity's **UI system** (Canvas, UI elements) for interfaces
- Use **Coroutines** for time-based operations and asynchronous tasks
- Apply Unity's **tag and layer system** for object categorization

## Project Structure
- Keep game logic in scripts; use Unity Editor for scene composition
- Use **Prefabs** for reusable game objects and UI elements
- Utilize Unity's **animation system** (Animator, Animation Clips)
- Apply Unity's built-in **lighting and post-processing effects**
- Use Unity's **asset bundle system** for efficient resource management

## Performance Considerations
- Use **object pooling** for frequently instantiated/destroyed objects
- Optimize draw calls by batching materials and using atlases
- Implement **LOD systems** for complex 3D models
- Use Unity's **Job System and Burst Compiler** for CPU-intensive operations
- Optimize physics performance with simplified collision meshes

## Error Handling & Debugging
- Use Unity's **Debug class** for logging (Debug.Log, Debug.LogWarning, Debug.LogError)
- Implement **try-catch blocks** for file I/O and network operations
- Use Unity's **assertion system** (Debug.Assert) for logical errors
- Utilize Unity's **profiler and frame debugger** for performance issues
- Implement custom error messages and debug visualizations

## Testing & Quality
- Use Unity's built-in **testing framework** for unit and integration testing
- Implement custom error messages and debug visualizations
- Follow Unity documentation and C# programming guides for best practices

